Fix two of the three cascading wiring bugs in `apps/server/src/services/relay/adapter-manager.ts`.

## Bug 1b — Wrong method name on the interface

The `meshCore?` field in `AdapterManagerDeps` declares `getAgent(id)` which does not exist on `MeshCore`. The real public API is `getProjectPath(agentId)`. Replace the ad-hoc inline interface with a named structural interface.

In `apps/server/src/services/relay/adapter-manager.ts`, replace the current `AdapterManagerDeps` interface definition:

```typescript
// BEFORE (lines ~48-58)
export interface AdapterManagerDeps {
  agentManager: ClaudeCodeAgentManagerLike;
  traceStore: TraceStoreLike;
  pulseStore?: PulseStoreLike;
  /** Optional RelayCore for binding subsystem initialization */
  relayCore?: RelayCoreLike;
  /** Optional MeshCore for enriching AdapterContext with agent info */
  meshCore?: {
    getAgent(id: string): { manifest: Record<string, unknown> } | undefined;
  };
}
```

With:
```typescript
/** Minimal MeshCore interface needed by AdapterManager for CWD resolution. */
export interface AdapterMeshCoreLike {
  getProjectPath(agentId: string): string | undefined;
}

export interface AdapterManagerDeps {
  agentManager: ClaudeCodeAgentManagerLike;
  traceStore: TraceStoreLike;
  pulseStore?: PulseStoreLike;
  /** Optional RelayCore for binding subsystem initialization */
  relayCore?: RelayCoreLike;
  /** Optional MeshCore for enriching AdapterContext with agent CWD resolution */
  meshCore?: AdapterMeshCoreLike;
}
```

The real `MeshCore` satisfies this interface structurally because it has a `getProjectPath(agentId: string): string | undefined` method at line 460 of `packages/mesh/src/mesh-core.ts`.

## Bug 1c — Wrong field name in buildContext()

The current `buildContext()` method at lines ~233-252 calls `this.deps.meshCore.getAgent(sessionId)` and accesses `agentInfo.manifest.directory`. Both are wrong. Replace the entire `buildContext()` method:

```typescript
/** Enrich AdapterContext with Mesh agent info if meshCore is available. */
buildContext(subject: string): AdapterContext | undefined {
  if (!this.deps.meshCore) return undefined;
  if (!subject.startsWith('relay.agent.')) return undefined;

  const agentId = subject.split('.')[2]; // relay.agent.{agentId}
  if (!agentId) return undefined;

  const projectPath = this.deps.meshCore.getProjectPath(agentId);
  if (!projectPath) return undefined;

  return {
    agent: {
      directory: projectPath,
      runtime: 'claude-code',
    },
  };
}
```

Note the variable is renamed from `sessionId` to `agentId` as part of the naming cleanup (Phase 5 of the spec). The `manifest` field is removed from the returned context since we only expose what we reliably have.

## Acceptance Criteria

- TypeScript compiles cleanly (`pnpm typecheck`)
- `AdapterMeshCoreLike` is exported from `adapter-manager.ts` for use in `index.ts`
- `buildContext()` no longer accesses `.manifest.directory` — it calls `getProjectPath()` directly
- The existing `adapter-manager.test.ts` tests continue to pass
- New tests added in task 1.3 cover the fixed `buildContext()` behavior

Fix Bug 1a: `apps/server/src/index.ts` constructs `adapterManager` inside the `if (relayEnabled)` block at ~line 116, but `meshCore` is initialized in the always-on block at ~line 143. This means `adapterManager` is always constructed without `meshCore`, so `buildContext()` immediately returns `undefined`.

## Current problematic initialization order

```
if (relayEnabled) {
  // Lines ~100-134
  adapterRegistry = new AdapterRegistry()
  traceStore = new TraceStore(db)
  relayCore = new RelayCore(...)
  adapterManager = new AdapterManager(adapterRegistry, adapterConfigPath, {
    agentManager,
    traceStore,
    pulseStore,
    relayCore,
    // meshCore is NOT here — it hasn't been initialized yet!
  })
  await adapterManager.initialize()
  relayCore.setAdapterContextBuilder(adapterManager.buildContext.bind(adapterManager))
}

// Always-on block — runs AFTER the relay block
// Lines ~136-169
meshCore = new MeshCore({ db, relayCore, signalEmitter, logger })
agentManager.setMeshCore(meshCore)
```

## Required fix: Split relay initialization into two sub-phases

The relay initialization block must be split. `adapterManager` construction (and its `initialize()` call) must move to AFTER `meshCore` is constructed.

**Phase A** (inside `if (relayEnabled)`, before meshCore):
```typescript
// Phase A: core relay infrastructure
const adapterRegistry = new AdapterRegistry();
adapterRegistry.setLogger(logger);
traceStore = new TraceStore(db);
relayCore = new RelayCore({ dataDir: relayDataDir, adapterRegistry, db, traceStore });
await relayCore.registerEndpoint('relay.system.console');
logger.info(`[Relay] RelayCore initialized (dataDir: ${relayDataDir})`);
```

**Phase B** (always-on block, same as current — meshCore init, no changes needed)

**Phase C** (inside `if (relayEnabled && relayCore)`, AFTER meshCore is initialized):
```typescript
// Phase C: adapter manager — now meshCore is available
const adapterConfigPath = path.join(dorkHome, 'relay', 'adapters.json');
adapterManager = new AdapterManager(adapterRegistry, adapterConfigPath, {
  agentManager,
  traceStore,
  pulseStore,
  relayCore,
  meshCore, // meshCore is now available!
});
await adapterManager.initialize();
relayCore.setAdapterContextBuilder(adapterManager.buildContext.bind(adapterManager));
logger.info('[Relay] AdapterManager initialized');
```

## Implementation notes

- `adapterRegistry` must be declared in the outer scope (like `relayCore`, `adapterManager`) so Phase C can reference it
- `adapterConfigPath` is a local derived from `dorkHome` — it can be a local const declared in Phase C
- `MeshCore` has no dependency on `AdapterManager`, so this reorder is safe per ADR-0062
- Phase C's try/catch should cover only the adapterManager construction/initialization, matching the existing error handling pattern. If `adapterManager` init fails, set `adapterManager = undefined` and log the error (non-fatal).
- The existing error logging (`setRelayInitError`) should remain in Phase A's catch block covering relayCore init
- Phase C failure must NOT cause `relayCore` or `meshCore` to become `undefined` — they are initialized independently

## Variable scope changes

Add to the global `let` declarations at the top of `start()` (or module-level):
```typescript
let adapterRegistry: AdapterRegistry | undefined;
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- When `DORKOS_RELAY_ENABLED=true` and Mesh is enabled, `adapterManager` is constructed with `meshCore` present
- `buildContext('relay.agent.{someUlid}')` returns a valid `AdapterContext` with `directory` set (not `undefined`)
- Relay init failure (Phase A) still prevents Phase C from running (guard on `relayCore` being defined)
- `pnpm typecheck` passes
- Server starts cleanly with `pnpm dev`
- The manual repro: two registered mesh agents can send relay messages to each other and receive responses in the correct project CWD

